segments.text: allowed him to work with me just before I entered the Air Force.

In the succeeding four years, he was able to develop a fairly substantial department that was grossly inadequate to take care of the community, but at least by numbers of people, it was beginning to be a department with some specialization.
However, shortly after I came back with the department,
Mr. Wingo went with the Ford Foundation and left the department without a head.
What year would that be?
That was in 1956 or early 57.
We had a fairly progressive city administration, and they recruited nationwide and brought in a new director of planning whose name was Merle Phillips.
You mentioned a progressive city administration.
Do you recall who the mayor was at that time?
Yes, it was a Tom Rogers.
He was a one-term mayor.
He did quite a bit for the community.
He was a very substantial mayor, but was not re-elected, perhaps because of that.
What was the background of the new city planning director?
The new city planning director was actually from Iowa.

by way of California, was primarily in physical planning, strong in subdivision and thoroughfare design, this sort of thing, and took a great deal of interest in the development of or the updating of the thoroughfare plan for the community.
Had the comprehensive plan for the city been updated during that period?
It was being updated piecemeal, in-house, without the benefit of consultants or extra help.
So consequently, it was dragging along, had been dragging along during Mr. Wingo's years.
And when the new director, Merle Phillips, came in, he was able to hire a number of young planners who came in and began to develop
pieces of this updated plan.
It seems rather remarkable.
The city had a staff, when he came in, of only seven planners.
Yet it was going through one of its most dramatic growth phases.
And it surely must have outstripped the plan documents and their relevance during that time.
I suppose the kind of seat of the pants and plan as you go was the way
current planning subdivisions and zoning cases had to be handled.
This is true.

So far as subdivisions go, for example, there was originally a few subdivisions that came through in the post-war years were handled sort of on an individual basis, where coordination between the city departments

sometimes non-existent or not very satisfactory so consequently a method was developed to route a cloth map around to all the agencies that were thought to have some interest you developed that method didn't you no this this was one that was was with the community uh i guess mr stock will probably develop this
They were essentially just routing a map around, a purported final map, and all of the city officials.
Well, this was a map.
A map only.
How long did it take to gather all the comments together?
Really, there were no comments.
They were just signatures.
So consequently, if the consulting engineer was skilled in browbeating the city officials to get their signatures, he could go ahead and get his map through reasonably promptly.
But it literally might take days or weeks, and not a whole lot of coordination, really.
Just a matter of, here's a map, look okay to you, yeah, it's fine, we'll sign here, type sort of.
That must have made it difficult if there were comments that were in conflict with each other.
This is right.
And sometimes it was possible to play off one serious objection to a,
say a circulation plan for a subdivision, against another comment from another city official.
It wasn't very satisfactory, but it was at least some way to sort of coordinate new subdivisions with what existed then as a city plan.
This was not satisfactory.
It took a lot of time on the part of the consultant.
It took a lot of time, and it wasn't possible for the city officials to really put a sufficient thought into the subdivision and its impact on the Long Range community.
The city had a very different relationship with the development community at that time.
have heard, at least, that up until a period in the 50s, the city engineering department designed the streets.
This is right.
This was a...
They designed the profiles of the streets.
Right.
This took some of the problems that we experienced in a fairly recent time away.
At least there was one agency that was totally
responsible for the design of streets.
And it occurs to me the only thing we have similar to that today is the design of the water and sewer system, which is done through local water utilities.
Yes, this is right.
Let's go back for a moment to the planning director who had just been hired.
This had been created about 1956, you said?
In about 50, 1957, Mr. Phillips was hired, and he was able to build the department up somewhat to the size it really should have been to accommodate the needs of the community.
So it grew from seven people to?
About 20 or so.
20 people.
And were there any other changes in the structure or administration of the department during that time?
Yes, it was divided.

once and for all into divisions at the time, advanced planning and current planning, and the semblance of a cartography section to provide for the special products that were needed in the planning process.
So at that time the city planning department became the creator and caretaker of the zoning maps?
Zoning maps and aerial photos and all the tools of the trade.
And Mr. Phillips, how long was he the planning director?
For a relatively short period of time.
Unfortunately, he found that the rather modest salary was scaled, and the prevalent in the community wasn't satisfactory, and he went into consulting a little on his own.
While he was planning director?
While he was planning director, and this, of course, got him into
a little bit of a problem.
Perhaps a conflict of interest occasionally.

Occasionally a conflict of interest, and ultimately he moved on, leaving behind the structure and the functioning organization and many of the, some of the people left in that period of time, receiving problems.
But most of the structure remained behind, and the leadership was taken over by the
a traffic engineer.
What was his name?
His name was Joseph Naden.
He's a man who's, I recall, much of our signalization system and such in the city traces back to him.
He was a good traffic engineer, wouldn't you say?
A very solid traffic engineer.
He had a good, strong method of expressing himself and was able to compromise at times
to make things work.
Was he able to effectively administer the planning department as well as his traffic engineering duties?
Really, he turned the...

He was able to keep together and to perform certain leadership functions, but he turned the actual planning functions over to the principals that were involved in the sections, saying something to the effect that, I don't know anything about planning, you take care of it, do the job, do what's required, we'll go on from there.

This was only a short-term situation, which incidentally lasted probably six months to a year, at which time the city fathers recruited a gentleman by the name of John Cunningham from the King County area of Washington State, who came into the area
with a good deal of knowledge and abilities.
Who was the mayor at that time?

I believe the mayor was Mayor Sightsinger, and he gave, the mayor and councilor gave a good deal of support at that time to Mr. Cunningham since we'd gone through several months or quite a few number of months of problems of one sort or the other.
And consequently, John wanted to get as much accomplished as he could while this honeymoon period was in effect.
And it was during this period that we were able to implement a number of ideas that we had had that for one reason or the other had not been able to bring them on board.
Let's go back to the, you mentioned the means of,
of routing a map for a subdivision plot to different agencies and how cumbersome that process was.
You had some different ideas about that, didn't you?
Yes.
This is one of the things that we were able to get into effect not too long after Mr. Cunningham came here.
I, over a long period of time, had developed the idea that the best way to coordinate

physical planning matters, including subdivisions and street and alley vacations and elements of the major thoroughfares plan, et cetera, et cetera, was through a meeting of key people in agencies and departments that were concerned with physical planning in the community.
I first had ideas on it when we were handling subdivision maps before the
I went into the Air Force.
When I came back, I had some definite ideas, along the ideas of a regular meeting of responsible city and county and state, possibly even federal officials, who were concerned with these matters.
And it wasn't until Mr. Cunningham came on board that I was actually able to
get the idea approved.
This concept I call the subdivision and coordinating committee, or subdivision coordinating committee.
Really, it involved more than coordinating subdivisions, but that was a nice, catchy name, and it seemed to stick, and still sticks to this day.
The first meeting was called, and it was the heads of

the public utilities in the community, electric, telephone, water, sewer, and gas, the City Engineering Department, representatives from some of the Department of Planning, Tax Department, and a few other agencies.

The concept was explained, a regular meeting on the same day each week to review these physical planning matters, and it was seized upon with great enthusiasm because many of these people felt they were not able to do the job because of the press of time and the press of trying to review these physical planning matters.
By mutual consent, Wednesday was selected as the day
that the committee would meet.
And with a few exceptions, mainly around the holidays, this committee has met for over 25 years, 58 to the present, another 30 years.
For a brief period, I served as the subdivision coordinator for the city.
And it was a tremendous vehicle for making the subdivision coordinator's job simpler.

generally kept referring to the Subdivision Coordinating Committee simply as the SCC, but it made the preparation of comments a painless task to have a meeting where we could discuss the subdivisions proposed or that had recently come in, provide a map copy to every member of the committee, standard routine two-week period after which comments were returned, and we could
then assemble one unified set of comments, discuss them, and present them in a timely fashion.
We were able to gather together the input and do our job within the 30-day time period the statute stipulates.
Exactly.
It always seemed it was kind of a joke that the SEC was held together with donuts.
It was kind of an interesting means of keeping it together that members alternated bringing a snack for each other.
Was this from the outset?
Was this delivered?
No, this really began when we were meeting for a period of time at the El Paso Electric Company meeting room.
And they started the tradition of coffee and donuts.
And that's where it began.
And then after we moved back to planning facilities, to city facilities, this tradition had just
established on a rotating basis by all the members, so it was not a big burden on anybody.
The Department Heads Development Coordinating Committee is another group that meets on a weekly basis.
This came about after John Cunningham took over, didn't it?
It came about, I guess, about 15 or 20 years after the SCC was established, and I believe that the basis

upon which it was established was probably a consultant had come into town and said, gee, it would be great if the department heads would get together and consider matters of zoning and subdivision and physical planning and coordinate these things, probably without even realizing that it had such a concept for all those years.
It does strike me that it was a bit of a duplication.
Today, the department heads development coordinating committee
reviews and virtually votes on matters of rezoning, and it's their decision which becomes the official staff position.
What was the process for making that official staff recommendation on matters of rezoning prior to the department head's meeting?
As far as zoning is concerned, this was a staff function of the Department of Planning as far as recommendations.
The SEC never was involved in zoning matters.
The staff would make its recommendations in accordance with the plan for the area, in accordance with the pros and cons, and really leave the decision to the planning commission.
They didn't make hard and fast recommendations.
They merely showed, laid out the groundwork so the commission could make an intelligent decision.
You refer to their decisions were based, of course, on the plan documents which existed.
And we were talking earlier about during the transition of leadership in the planning department, the comprehensive plan was being updated on a more or less piecemeal basis.
Prior to John Cunningham taking over the department, was that task completed?
Really, I can't say that it was ever completed.
But there was a constant review of various elements of the plan.
And this process continued after John Cunningham came.
So rather than a ever so often complete update of the plan, it was simply the ongoing process that it always is.
It was exactly an ongoing process of elements, first one element and the other, so that it was a fairly living kind of a document, fairly well updated.
never really formally prepared and published.
Not necessarily compiled into a single document and taken in one fell swoop for approval by the Council.
Correct.
Was the Council aware of the planned document?
Was there a semblance of official approval of the planning thinking as to what was going on?
Yes, I think there was.
It was easy to refer to this nebulous document with all these elements that had been
worked on, and I think there's a fair degree of comprehension that it existed and fairly well accepted by the council and by other governmental entities.
And awareness and tacit approval without necessarily an official or systematic process for it.
Correct.
It seemed for a while that the planning department was a stepchild.
I know it wasn't necessarily housed with the rest of the city offices.
Do you recall some of the different facilities that the department was located in?
Originally, when I went to work for the department, it was in the old city hall.
And it was later moved to, because of space requirements and the fact that the city government was going, to a separate lease facility
on Kansas Street.
This was a fairly modest facility, but it was probably three times the space that it had in the old city hall.
It stayed there for a number of years through the early and middle 50s, then moved when, after Mr. Wingo had left, and actually after Mr. Phillips had left, it moved to another facility

at I think it was 212 South Campbell, a rather large old equipment sales building, very large reinforced concrete, lots of space, which was piecemeal remodeled over a long period of time to provide for meeting rooms and various office facilities, even a coffee shop where the subdivision coordinating committee was.
conceived and created.

From there the department was moved to another location and I don't recall the address but it's another separate building and it wasn't until the new city hall was constructed that the department actually became a part of the rest of the city.
The fact that the department wasn't necessarily located in the same building as the
elected leaders and city council chambers and some of the other city departments.
Do you think that implied anything in terms of relationship with planning, or was that simply a circumstantial space?
I think it really depended upon who viewed it.
Some people probably said, get those ivory tower people out of the way and don't have to worry about them.
I think the department did a pretty good idea.
It got it away from politics somewhat and was able to function in its own way independently and then make its presentation to the governmental entities at the right time.
It was a degree of independence that was created that way, I think.
I'm going to ask you a question now that is asked of every person that has been interviewed for this.
If you could
think about it for a moment and tell us what you would consider to be the five or so major events that have affected the planning and development of El Paso.
Well, you'd have to go ahead and say that the phenomenal growth after the war, just completely outpacing the ability of government to provide services,
for a period of time.
Perhaps this gave more awareness on the part of the elected officials of the importance and need for planning.
This is right.
Because of this inadequacy, I think there's a great deal more recognition that
They needed the help of professionals in providing for the extension of the services required to serve this growing community.
The much heralded Shama's Isle settlement certainly was a major effect on the community and caused a great deal of disruption.
opened up avenues for improvement in the south side area.
Another huge impact, particularly the east-west freeway, Interstate 10, totally disrupted the older area of town and created changes that are continuing to this day.
Redirected our growth forever.
Exactly.
And to a lesser degree, the north-south
were able to accommodate.
Now I don't think it's nearly the same.
Perhaps its impact is yet to be felt.
Exactly.
Another very large effect, back in about 1954, the Public Service Board, which provides the water for the community, perceived the need to stabilize and to secure as much water resource as possible
in order to accomplish this, purchased from individuals, sometimes with a threat of condemnation, but more often a friendly purchase.
And from the state, huge areas of land, particularly the north, west, and northeast, everything essentially north of the city limits from the Fort Bliss Military Reservation
east to the Mexico State line north of the city.
This did one very large thing.
It placed under public protection land which could be exploited on a more controlled basis and developed to provide for public facilities and an orderly disposal of the land.
to provide for more orderly growth pattern in that area.
Consequently, you've had a little bit more stable development in those areas than you have to the east and southeast.
In fact, a good amount of the land that's still held by El Paso Water Utilities is yet to be developed, and plans are being undertaken
Who knows?
It may be that the northernmost portion of northeast El Paso will develop along the lines of Cielo Vista, with the public body being the governing force of the development pattern.

The difference, really, between the airport development in Cielo Vista and the public service board concept of development in northeast, the public service board wanted to stay out of the master planning area and let private enterprise
working in conjunction with the governmental forces, developed the area to its highest and best use in accordance with the master plan for the city.
There was a great deal less governmental input, except from the Department of Planning, in the northeast area and the northwest area, land that was owned by the Public Service Board originally.
than there was in the airport area.
Of course, beyond this airport area, it was at the bottom.
The Sierra Vista area, by the way, was about 3,000 acres, I believe.
Sizable land park.
Right.
And the public service board owned and owns about 35 or so sections of land.
Okay.

Incidentally, this land has been sold by the Public Service Board on a sealed bid basis in increments in a way that public facilities like school sites, arterials, park sites have been reserved and provided to
the various agencies at normal cost, saving the public money, or at no cost at all in some cases.
Today, El Paso is a very different city than some of the period we've described.
We're a city of over 400,000.
The city of Juarez, the population estimates vary from a million and a half to who knows what.
We've seen a tremendous amount of growth.
We have some problems with our economy.
Tell me, what do you see as the future direction of El Paso city planning efforts, say, in the next 10 years?
The biggest problem that El Paso has and the biggest impact on planning and on our area really is totally beyond the local community, in my opinion.
We're faced with an immigration situation, a border situation here, over which the city itself has no control.
We're talking about some of the wave of immigration we've seen over the last few years.
We're talking about literally millions of Mexicans, Central Americans, and South Americans who are moving north trying to get to this country, and a lot of them
are impacting the El Paso area.
We've seen it through the tremendous growth in Juarez.

We've seen it through the tremendous border crossing problems that we've had, the impact on the border patrol trying to control immigration, illegal immigration to the extent that they have, unsuccessfully to a large degree.
We've seen it in the

invasion of the public facilities that we have in the community where we're actually and in fact are providing parks for the city of El Paso and the city of Juarez with all the supporting taxes coming from the city.

city of el paso that's true we also see it in our county hospital facilities we're seeing it in the county hospital facilities we're seeing it all that the health services that are available where illegal people people from another country come in take advantage of the facilities pay nothing in the way of taxes or direct contribution and then disappear yet el paso is a poor community and el paso is a poor community

and it's becoming poorer on account of these external influences and the rating the county judge for example presented the bill just this year i believe it was to the federal government for eight million dollars for services that had been rendered by the county hospital to
